WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.250 --> 00:00:16.939
When Christopher Columbus crossed the atlantic in 1492, he carried with him diseases

00:00:17.369 --> 00:00:23.029
which all but quite touched the native Indian population.

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:32.389
Their revenge, according to history, was to send back to Europe the scourge of syphilis.

00:00:36.390 --> 00:00:42.050
But now, a skeleton unearthed in an English monastery can at last put the record straight.

00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:46.639
This is the true story of syphilis.

00:01:07.210 --> 00:01:09.210
This story begins in Hull.

00:01:18.450 --> 00:01:25.700
When the city planners decided to build a new magistrate's court next to a multi-story car park in the town center,

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:31.549
it gave the local archaeological unit the chance to survey the site first for ancient remains and artifacts.

00:01:34.829 --> 00:01:42.829
Working within a very limited time frame, the team worked day and night, digging out what they suspected might be the remains of a medieval friary.

00:01:46.950 --> 00:01:53.089
By the end of the dig, they had unearthed more than 240 skeletons and countless artifacts,

00:01:56.909 --> 00:02:01.188
information which painted a detailed picture of a Shadowy medieval world:

00:02:04.829 --> 00:02:11.869
A heady mix of religion and riches, medicine and morality, sex and disease.

00:02:29.930 --> 00:02:36.999
You have a complete ground plan for a medieval monastery, which is almost unheard of; it's a major piece of archaeological work.

00:02:40.549 --> 00:02:45.819
John Bugless is the project leader for what has become known as the "Magistrates Court Site,"

00:02:46.549 --> 00:02:49.959
responsible for recording every last detail of the excavation.

00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:53.500
We're fortunate with this site that preservation conditions are excellent.

00:02:53.700 --> 00:03:00.700
We have surviving coffins, textile fragments, leather objects; we have bodies that still got shoes on and things like that.

00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:02.640
So we have really good skeletons to look at.

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:16.540
One skeleton in particular from the hull site was sent to rewrite history.

00:03:20.120 --> 00:03:26.140
Very soon after we got the skeletons, we started to see things that were rather unusual.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.600
And particularly, there was a lot of infectious disease in the site,

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:37.020
including what we thought were classic cases of syphilis.

00:03:40.400 --> 00:03:48.420
And this one here, 1216 - this 25 to 35-year-old male - is one good example. In fact, it's the best example.

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:57.040
The skeletons from the Hull site were sent to the University of Bradford for analysis.

00:03:57.040 --> 00:04:02.340
It's usually incredibly difficult to diagnose the cause of death so long after the event,

00:04:02.569 --> 00:04:05.229
as many diseases leave no trace at all on the bones.

00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:09.400
But syphilis is one of the few exceptions.

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:16.700
Charlotte Roberts is an expert in paleopathology, the archaeology of disease.

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:22.420
Can she be sure that skeleton number 1216 really did have syphilis?

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:28.680
There are a number of changes in the skeleton for recognizing syphilis.

00:04:32.090 --> 00:04:38.979
If we focus on the skull, you can see immediately that there's something wrong.

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:46.600
Normally - if I just get a skull that's not affected by the disease

00:04:47.360 --> 00:04:52.780
- you would expect to see a smooth surface on this part of the skull.

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:59.200
But here, you've got pockmark lesion; holes in the bone.

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:02.440
It's something that people call carry sicca.

00:05:03.620 --> 00:05:09.820
It's characteristic of venereal syphilis. We don't see it in any of the other syndromes.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:15.000
So I would say that's characteristic of the disease.

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:20.720
The other thing on this skull is that you've got a hole in the palate,

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:22.200
the connection between the nose and the mouth,

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:26.600
and that's commonly seen in syphilis.

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:34.839
We move down the skeleton what we see again is bone formation and bone destruction.

00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:40.120
I think probably the most florid bone formation is actually on the leg bones.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:42.880
This is a thigh bone.

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:48.160
And you can see the whole length of it

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:54.220
has got the formation of bone we also got some destructive lesions here

00:05:55.460 --> 00:05:57.460
and here.

00:06:04.420 --> 00:06:07.020
We look at one of the lower leg bones.

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:11.180
Again, you see the same sort of changes that you see here,

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:16.380
but also you get a massive amount of bone formation on the front of this lower leg bone,

00:06:16.380 --> 00:06:20.340
which people call a "saber shin" because it looks like a saber.

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:29.769
Imagine the inflammation, swelling of these limbs, the redness, the heat, the pain.

00:06:33.020 --> 00:06:38.800
Apart from skeleton 1216, the site contained two more classic cases of the disease,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:43.320
and there were characteristic signs of syphilis in more than 60% of the bodies.

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:49.780
But all these people were buried in the sanctuary walls of a deeply religious community.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:57.800
And syphilis is a venereal disease that is contract through sexual intercourse.

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:01.540
So what kind of religious community was this?

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:30.460
The building belonged to a Christian order called the Augustinian Friars,

00:07:32.360 --> 00:07:36.939
and this complex of cloisters, living accommodation and church was the friary.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:46.420
It was one of the first to be established in England, and in 1539, the last to be destroyed.

00:07:52.610 --> 00:07:58.809
The brothers were not rich, like some other religious orders of the time; they were supposed to beg for a living.

00:08:01.460 --> 00:08:07.420
These friars were the social services of their day: They looked after the poor at the time.

00:08:07.420 --> 00:08:11.460
They were skilled in medicine and they cared for the sick whether they were rich or poor.

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:17.240
Their good works and religious calling put them beyond reproach.

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:20.580
And they were, of course, celebate.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.780
But the skeletons from the Hull friary proved the presence of a sexually transmitted disease.

00:08:43.680 --> 00:08:47.620
What had gone so perversely wrong amongst the brothers here?

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:54.900
There was more evidence from the dig which could not easily be explained away.

00:08:55.600 --> 00:08:59.420
A dozen bodies were found with a wooden rod buried alongside them,

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:03.620
leading to the suspicion that these friars belonged to a flagellation sect.

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:08.440
We have a series of rods which are quite short.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:13.800
They're sort of about that long and they still have the bark on them. And they're hazel, nice and whippy.

00:09:14.560 --> 00:09:17.400
And there has been a suggestion they're actually flagellation rods.

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:21.100
Because at this particular time, with plague sweeping through various parts of Europe,

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:27.780
there was quite a strong movement - particularly on the continent - for self-flagellation and hair shirts.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.420
And you suffer more in this life; therefore, the afterlife becomes better.

00:09:38.420 --> 00:09:42.620
The Augustinian brothers were experts on the afterlife.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.260
They made a lot of money from death.

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:51.400
They sold candles and winding sheets for the dead.

00:09:51.890 --> 00:09:57.189
They presided over funerals, held vigils and set masses for the souls of the departed,

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:04.340
all paid for by the wealthy merchant and aristocratic classes in order to save their souls,

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:08.100
buying their way into heaven through the industry of the friars.

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:13.079
This put the brothers in a powerful position.

00:10:14.529 --> 00:10:20.099
If they dispensed with their vow of poverty as easily as they seem to have broken their vow of celibacy,

00:10:20.649 --> 00:10:23.669
they could make a fortune out of the misfortune of others.

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:44.190
This medieval will from Hall shows that the system was certainly open to corruption.

00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:48.000
We have two surviving wills from this period of time.

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:55.920
And one of them actually states that a sum of money is to be put aside per friar who attends mass for this person's funeral.

00:10:56.110 --> 00:11:00.959
Which is terribly open to abuse, because you can just load up x number of friars;

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:06.000
you could grab friars from every house in the area and bring them in and bulk your funds up.

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:18.160
The Augustinians were not a closed order of monks, shut away from the temptations of the world in a life of quiet contemplation.

00:11:26.060 --> 00:11:30.100
The priory was deliberately positioned in the commercial heart of the time,

00:11:30.620 --> 00:11:35.440
wedged in between the houses of wealthy merchants and the key side of the bustling port.

00:11:36.950 --> 00:11:42.309
One of the things is the trade that comes into Hull and makes its wealth its wine trade coming in from Spain.

00:11:43.250 --> 00:11:50.530
The volume of wine being imported is enormous - a million and a half liters a year is a staggeringly large amount of wine,

00:11:50.900 --> 00:11:57.549
a lot of which would be consumed locally. So you would seem to think that there could well be a high degree of carousing.

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:06.130
The site in Hull uncovered large collections of the imported wine jugs,

00:12:06.650 --> 00:12:10.749
evidence that at least some of the carousing was going on within the fiery walls.

00:12:12.980 --> 00:12:16.090
But this does not mean that they were necessarily dissolute.

00:12:17.150 --> 00:12:22.479
Medieval monks probably drank four times as much alcohol as people drink in England today,

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:25.660
and the Hull friars were no different.

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:40.300
The whipping rods, if that is what they were, point more towards a form of medieval Christian devotion than sexual deviancy.

00:12:44.060 --> 00:12:48.180
If they were corrupt, the evidence is no more than circumstantial.

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:57.280
We are left would be astonishing evidence of the bones.

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:02.739
How can we explain the presence of syphilis within the friary walls?

00:13:07.720 --> 00:13:15.400
Channel Four commissioned experts at Bradford University to make a computerized map plotting the site of each skeleton,

00:13:15.400 --> 00:13:18.420
superimposed on the outline of the friary.

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:31.440
Augustinian friars sold burial plots within their church;

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:37.600
the nearer the altar, the nearer to God, and so the more expensive the plot.

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:42.780
The most prestigious plots were reserved for the senior friars

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:46.060
and for the rich merchants who paid for this privilege.

00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:58.029
The map shows exactly where the bones of skeleton 1216 were buried:

00:14:05.180 --> 00:14:08.049
In a prime spot close to the altar.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:22.040
So which was he? A rich nobleman? Or an esteemed member of the monastic community?

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:25.000
We will never know.

00:14:26.420 --> 00:14:30.580
The Hull site cannot prove that syphilis was rampant amongst the friars,

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:36.699
but it does show that it was widespread amongst the elite of this prosperous community at that time.

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:40.740
So when was that time?

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:50.640
When did skeleton number 1216 die?

00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:56.200
The evidence from the dig suggests that he died in the 1300s.

00:14:57.740 --> 00:15:01.569
But if this was true, this was electrifying information.

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:12.600
For history records that syphilis originated amongst the Native American Indians,

00:15:14.020 --> 00:15:19.440
and was contracted by the crew of Christopher Columbus during his voyages to the New World.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:25.240
On returning to the Old World, the new disease grew into a plague of epidemic proportions.

00:15:25.540 --> 00:15:33.020
First among the Spanish soldiers of the siege of Naples in 1495 before spreading remorselessly through Europe.

00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:50.200
If the Hull site could be dated to before 1492,

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:59.420
then the disease must have existed in the Old World prior to Columbus's journey, and history would have to be rewritten.

00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:06.560
And to help them date the burials, the archaeologists at Hull had a red piece of luck:

00:16:10.720 --> 00:16:15.989
The waterlogged conditions of the site had preserved a remarkable number of wooden coffins,

00:16:16.720 --> 00:16:20.459
ideal and rare material from which to get a reliable date.

00:16:22.540 --> 00:16:24.000
It's a very unusual find.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:31.800
There are only ten sites that have generated significant quantities of waterlogged coffin boards across the whole country for the past fifty years.

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:35.520
So it's a very unusual find, and this is by far the biggest assemblage.

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:46.760
Ian Tires, from the dendrochronology unit in Sheffield, took over 300 samples back to his lab.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:54.000
The critical thing that we were supposed to be sorting out was the dating of the coffins themselves,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.860
to help sort the stratigraphy and help put a timetable to the burials.

00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:05.200
You can see that we have wide rings and narrow rings are effectively reflecting the conditions

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:09.640
under which the tree was growing; whether it was having a good summer or a bad summer, as far as growth is concerned.

00:17:09.850 --> 00:17:17.429
And those are act like a fingerprint through time - the pattern of narrow and wide rings is unique over a number of millennia.

00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:25.400
Having recorded the measurements for each sample, Ian then fed all the information into a central database

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:28.280
to find a match which would give him a definite date.

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:33.570
From our dating perspective,

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:38.500
we can date their year and indeed the season of the year that the trees are felled

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:45.980
And those that we have bark age for, so the year the trees were cut down are all in the 1340s and the 1360s.

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:57.420
The date from the dendrochronology lab puts the coffins at between 1340 and 1369.

00:17:58.380 --> 00:18:01.620
This is not in itself particularly surprising.

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:06.160
All the indications from the dig - the pottery, the historical records -

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:11.960
all show a date around the middle of the 14th century, and the wood dating is right in the middle of this.

00:18:15.290 --> 00:18:22.389
But of course this information from the site in Hull has sent shockwaves through the archaeological and historical worlds.

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:31.480
Because syphilis is not supposed to have been in this country - in Europe, even - until Columbus brought the disease back from America.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:40.600
150 years after skeleton 1216 was buried in the nave of an Augustinian friary on the northeast coast of England.

00:18:44.500 --> 00:18:48.300
Who can history blame for the scourge of syphilis?

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:55.760
In 1493, Christopher Columbus returned home to Europe with news of a New World.

00:18:57.100 --> 00:19:01.650
History records that he brought a new disease with him, too: Syphilis.

00:19:03.070 --> 00:19:10.950
But now, the discovery and Hull of skeletons bearing the scars of syphilis undermines this 500-year-old version of history.

00:19:12.780 --> 00:19:18.020
For these bodies were buried 150 years before Columbus set sail.

00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:24.020
So the question now is, who really gave syphilis to whom?

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:37.560
To understand, we need to look closely of the reasons why people have always believed this Columbus theory.

00:19:40.450 --> 00:19:47.309
In the closing years of the 15th century, a young ambitious scholar described a new disease sweeping through Europe.

00:19:47.800 --> 00:19:54.220
In recent times, I have seen a disease which is so cruel, so distressing, so appalling,

00:19:54.240 --> 00:20:01.020
that until now nothing so horrifying, nothing more terrible or disgusting has ever been known on this earth.

