00:39:32.410 --> 00:39:36.480
Crucially, they widened their search beyond what the bones alone could tell them.

00:39:39.640 --> 00:39:43.109
They read Latin texts and studied Roman medicine.

00:39:44.049 --> 00:39:49.229
They found evidence everywhere that convinced them that syphilis was rampant in the city.

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:57.600
There's various strings of evidence from written sources, from the cultural functioning of the city,

00:39:57.600 --> 00:40:06.200
from the business of prostitutes, from public houses, from the fact that it was a trading center and a sea port.

00:40:06.200 --> 00:40:12.000
And evidence that we can see on bones are all coming together to support the hypothesis

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:16.000
of the presence of syphilis in the classical antiquity of Europe.

00:40:18.400 --> 00:40:24.620
By looking at the wider social context of the disease, the Hennebergs have not just demonstrated

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:28.200
that the disease has been around in Europe for thousands of years,

00:40:28.200 --> 00:40:32.180
they have also found the key to unlock the syphilis enigma.

00:40:32.940 --> 00:40:36.420
The question is no longer, "Who gave it to whom?"

00:40:36.420 --> 00:40:43.020
There is simply not enough bone evidence yet, on either side of the Atlantic, to settle the argument for good.

00:40:55.080 --> 00:41:00.400
But add to the evidence of the bones an understanding of the way of life of these places,

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:03.820
and the true story of syphilis begins to unfold.

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:15.740
Syphilis is a survivor, and to survive it has mutated to adapt to different climates and different societies.

